<p>In 1772, wool merchant Fran√ßois Adrien Van den Bogaert commissioned a garden pavilion for Den Wolsack, his house in Antwerp. On the first floor is a bibliophile&#8217;s lavatory, in which the bowl is concealed in a fancifully rendered stack of books.</p>
<p>The volumes on the surrounding shelves aren&#8217;t real; they&#8217;re made of wood covered with leather.</p>
